		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="Printed letterhead."></p>
				<p rend="align(center)"><persName>D. J. WORKUM</persName>&#44;</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">MANUFACTURER AND JOBBER OF</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">HATS&#44; CAPS &#38; GENTS&#39; FURNISHING GOODS&#44;</p>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>NO. 42 WOODWARD AVENUE</placeName>.</p>
				<p rend="align(center)">&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;</p>
				<p><placeName>Detroit</placeName>&#44; <date>Febr 14 1867</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Phild</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(10)">My Dear friend</p>
				<p>I rejoice to learn of your safe return &#38; I<lb/> trust with <sic>renewd</sic> rigour &#38; strength  I have<lb/> just read this months Occident&#8212;disappointed&#8212;I<lb/> fully anticipated to read your full account of places<lb/> visited their synagogues.<lb/>  <hi rend="underline">Prepress</hi> numbers &#38;c<lb/> It would prove interesting to your readers&#44;<lb/>  None regretted the sudden loss of that Pious good<lb/> woman <persName>Mrs. Osterman</persName> &#40;Peace on her Soul&#41; than<lb/> myself &#38; would more rejoice at her not forgetting<lb/> the worthy in her will.  I cannot but congratulate<lb/> you &#38; I doubt not you will find it useful<lb/> for I presume your Income not as great as<lb/> to enable you to keep a large Bank account<lb/> to your Credit.  I have now resided here<lb/> nearly Two Years without joining either Congregation<lb/>  The Polish Minhag I do not so much object<lb/> to as the mixing with its worshipers.  You may blame</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>me but were you here in my situation you would<lb/> act the same.  My immediate kindest &#38; best Friends<lb/> &#40;Friends not only in words but noble actions&#41; are there<lb/> Connected with the Reform Synagogue my <add>&#63;</add> &#38;<lb/> visitors are the same while the others I know not<lb/> &#38; from what I see of them care not to know<lb/>  I have at times visited their Synagogue &#38; the service<lb/> is not what I admire.  Give me the <sic>Pourtugese</sic><lb/> service above all others for solemnity.  The<lb/> Minister of the <placeName>Revard St</placeName> Synagogue <persName>Mr Epstine</persName><lb/> is a very talented man  He Preaches every <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> alternately English&#44; German his Synagogue is well<lb/> attended.  He has that happy oratory of mastering his<lb/> hearers feel his words &#38; frequently the whole audience<lb/> are in tears at the strength of his Inspiring words<lb/>  The Polish Synagogue is fairly attended they have a Hazan<lb/> but no Preacher&#44; <persName>Mrs Hart</persName> &#38; family write<lb/> with myself in kind regards</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">With your friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">Isaac Hart</persName></p>
				<p>We have formed a <add>social</add> Club of about 45 Members&#44;<lb/> Cards&#44; Dramatic Performances&#44; Lectures&#44; Concerts Balls<lb/> &#38;c.  Two Performances in English &#38; one in German<lb/> by the Members <add>their</add> wives &#38; Sisters was played equal to any stage</p>
		
